{
  "query": "What are the effects on butterfly and moth communities of opening up forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 14 studies on clearing/opening patches, cleared areas often had higher butterfly species richness but lower moth species richness than unmanaged, coppiced, or closed-canopy forest, and butterfly richness sometimes declined over the first three years after clearing [3938]. Butterfly abundance generally increased in cleared patches, including for several fritillaries and other species, with larger clearings supporting higher butterfly richness and abundance, while wider rides had lower macro\u2011moth abundance than standard rides or mature forest; a European review reported small-patch clearing benefitted 19/67 butterfly species of conservation concern [3938]. In coppiced woodland, communities of butterflies and moths differed with coppice age, coppiced sites contained more unique macro\u2011moth species than mature forest but had lower macro\u2011moth richness and abundance, while butterfly species richness and abundance were higher in coppiced than unmanaged woodland, with several studies reporting higher butterfly abundance 2\u201315 years after coppicing; persistence of some fritillary populations was greater in coppiced/young woodland, and increases were also reported following coppicing alongside other measures [3939]. With thinning, several studies (often with additional treatments such as prescribed burning, mulching, or nearby felling) found increased butterfly richness and abundance 1\u20134 years after management; partially cleared plots had higher butterfly but lower moth species richness than closed\u2011canopy forest, while in one tropical site fruit\u2011feeding butterflies had similar richness and abundance to unmanaged forest but rarer species were less frequently caught in thinned forest [3940].",
